subs.text: @davewiner Yes, there is Require.js, but that’s ancient by JS standards. Otherwise, you might want to use a bundler, as it will take Node packages just fine. They’ve all vastly reduced their upfront configuration needs lately.
subs.rawText: @davewiner Yes, there is Require.js, but that’s ancient by JS standards. Otherwise, you might want to use a bundler, as it will take Node packages just fine. They’ve all vastly reduced their upfront configuration needs lately.

subs.text: @davewiner Because it requires a synchronous cascade of requests, as require works at runtime. With ES Modules, the engine knows ahead of time what you will need and can parse some modules while you fetch others and run them all the same time.
subs.rawText: @davewiner Because it requires a synchronous cascade of requests, as require works at runtime. With ES Modules, the engine knows ahead of time what you will need and can parse some modules while you fetch others and run them all the same time.

subs.text: @davewiner With dynamic import() it can also work at runtime, but being an async function, it lets you do work meanwhile (for example, show a spinner or keep processing user interaction).
subs.rawText: @davewiner With dynamic import() it can also work at runtime, but being an async function, it lets you do work meanwhile (for example, show a spinner or keep processing user interaction).

subs.text: @davewiner It’s worth noting that ES Modules already work in browser and Node; and they do take relative paths and absolute URLs. If you want to settle into something that works for both, that would be my bet.
subs.rawText: @davewiner It’s worth noting that ES Modules already work in browser and Node; and they do take relative paths and absolute URLs. If you want to settle into something that works for both, that would be my bet.
